<div id="subtree-container" class="subtree-container"><div class="aea2d7dde423afa7ad9351a0886150a8-scss b51b00c1669ad99a1c607cd1e77c2824-scss" style="inset: 365px 269px 0px 0px; justify-content: flex-end;"><div class="afeebf1df237d4103108ba40799802d6-scss"><div class="c13443431e58facf06f9d12490b92a82-scss" style="width: 90vw; max-width: 8.5in;"><div class="_0df5ec6b9902d7d22ccfa3ebb4f35211-scss">Pipes and Fittings - Ratios</div><div class="e5e059a27f4c194020f0d961a3cb5989-scss" dir="auto"><div class="fr-view"><p id="isPasted">Calculate the length of the pipes, as illustrated in Figure 11, adding a ratio that represents the length of the fittings, both in meters.&nbsp;</p>
<p>The magnitude of the applied ratio should consider system type and its diameter, considering that these factors can impact the total network length, and therefore, the total cost estimate.&nbsp;</p>
<p>This method provides an approximate estimate of the network length and is predominantly applied in preliminary project phases.</p>
